The Mighty Zoltan wrote:Pokrface wrote:Turning on either tap here results in hot water. The "cold" tap eventually produces water in the mid-70s, but it takes 30-40 seconds to do so.I am going to ask, because I am not the only one wondering...Where the fuck is "here"?Houston. In the winter the water is actually cold, but in summer, any water that's in the pipes in the house gets heated to ridiculous levels; you have to let it run until you get to water that has been sitting underground before you get anything even resembling lukewarm. Even then, it's not going to be cold by any stretch; if you want actual cold water, you need a refrigerator or water cooler. Which is fine, because the water tastes like ass, so you won't be drinking it anyway.
